      "message": "tl;dr: setEnabled doesn\u0027t work here since level dropdown is a \u003cdiv\u003e.  Tried switching to UI.ToolbarButton, but it has a different enabled-state color, so I opted to introduce this new \u0027disabled\u0027 class.\n\n\n\nSadly, setEnabled(false) does not affect the console level dropdown selector at all, it still responds to click events and looks the same.  setEnabled(false) does `this.element.disabled \u003d !enabled`, which only affects \"actually disabled\" elements (e.g. button, input, select https://www.w3.org/TR/html5/disabled-elements.html ), not \u003cdiv\u003es or \u003cspan\u003es which make up the level dropdown\u0027s ToolbarText and ToolbarItem.\n\nAn alternative that I considered was switching the console level dropdown to use UI.ToolbarButton with turnIntoSelect().  We already have a grayed out style for disabled buttons, however, enabled buttons look different from enabled ToolbarText.  ToolbarButtons with a select were given an extra dark color specifically for DeviceMode ( https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/e182ebe11e040ba0f4834ddd5da5a79b4467f906 ).",
